<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="527" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,220,1491]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,220,243]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Guimarães &amp; Ferreira-Jr, 2017" authorityName="Guimarães &amp; Ferreira-Jr" authorityYear="2017" box="[274,507,220,243]" class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Canthysellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="527" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="putkarot" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[274,507,220,243]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Canthysellus putkarot</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[513,596,220,243]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be distinguished from other species in the genus by the following characteristics: large size, 
<quantity box="[657,815,252,275]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.375" metricValueMax="3.4" metricValueMin="3.35" pageId="6" pageNumber="527" unit="mm" value="3.375" valueMax="3.4" valueMin="3.35">3.35–3.40 mm</quantity>
; pronotum and elytra smooth (
<figureCitation box="[159,225,284,307]" captionStart="Figs 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,188,982,1001]" captionTargetBox="[155,1114,233,950]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[151,1126,229,953]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–4. Habitus of Canthysellus species in lateral and dorsal view: 1 – C. kukrutkato sp. nov.; 2 – C. putkarot sp. nov.; 3 – C. omawe sp. nov.; 4 – C. yawari sp. nov. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315621" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315621/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); prosternal process completely covered by short setae; median lobe of aedeagus, in lateral aspect, elongate and thin with dorsobasal margin sharply narrowing before midlength (
<figureCitation box="[159,265,348,371]" captionStart="Figs 5–8" captionStartId="4.[151,188,1505,1524]" captionTargetBox="[204,1072,228,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[195,1082,219,1480]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 5–8.Aedeagi of Canthysellus: a – median lobe, left lateral aspect, b – same, dorsal aspect, c – same, right lateral aspect, d – left lateral lobe (paramere), e – right lateral lobe. 5 – C. kukrutkato sp. nov.; 6 – C. putkarot sp. nov.; 7 – C. omawe sp. nov.; 8 – C. yawari sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315625" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315625/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Figs 6a, c</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="527" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,220,1491]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,432,380,403]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">
Description of 
<typeStatus box="[325,427,380,403]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
Body outline, in dorsal view oval (
<figureCitation box="[826,895,380,403]" captionStart="Figs 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,188,982,1001]" captionTargetBox="[155,1114,233,950]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[151,1126,229,953]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–4. Habitus of Canthysellus species in lateral and dorsal view: 1 – C. kukrutkato sp. nov.; 2 – C. putkarot sp. nov.; 3 – C. omawe sp. nov.; 4 – C. yawari sp. nov. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315621" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315621/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Guimarães &amp; Ferreira-Jr, 2017" authorityName="Guimarães &amp; Ferreira-Jr" authorityYear="2017" box="[977,1126,380,403]" class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Canthysellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="527" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kukrutkato" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[977,1126,380,403]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">C. kukrutkato</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,236,412,435]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,220,1491]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis box="[181,243,444,467]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Color</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[261,330,444,467]" captionStart="Figs 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,188,982,1001]" captionTargetBox="[155,1114,233,950]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[151,1126,229,953]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–4. Habitus of Canthysellus species in lateral and dorsal view: 1 – C. kukrutkato sp. nov.; 2 – C. putkarot sp. nov.; 3 – C. omawe sp. nov.; 4 – C. yawari sp. nov. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315621" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315621/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Head and pronotum light reddish-brown. Elytra blackish, each elytron with four light reddish-brown maculae: one laterally, a second on disc, both just anterior to midlength of elytron, and a third near suture, these three markings appearing as an arched and interrupted transverse band; finally, a fourth short transverse macula on distal third. Ventral surface light reddish-brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,220,1491]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis box="[181,247,604,627]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Head.</emphasis>
Surface smooth and shiny. Antennae and palpi similar to those in 
<taxonomicName authority="Guimarães &amp; Ferreira-Jr, 2017" authorityName="Guimarães &amp; Ferreira-Jr" authorityYear="2017" box="[979,1126,604,627]" class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Canthysellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="527" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kukrutkato" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[979,1126,604,627]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">C. kukrutkato</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,234,636,659]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,220,1491]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis box="[181,266,668,691]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Thorax.</emphasis>
Pronotum smooth and shiny, with transversal row of punctures bearing long and slender setae in anterior margin. Prosternum with dense, transverse tuft of four stiff setae at middle of discal surface (
<figureCitation box="[429,495,732,755]" captionStart="Figs 9–10" captionStartId="8.[151,188,900,919]" captionTargetBox="[202,1078,222,882]" captionTargetId="figure-259@8.[199,1081,219,886]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 9–10. Prosternum, meso- and metaventrum and noterid platform (metacoxae) of Canthysellus, depicting distribution of setae. 9 – C. buqueti (Laporte, 1835); 10 – C. omawe sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315627" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315627/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); line of setae continuous medially, not extending beyond lateral margins of prosternal process. Prosternal process and noterid platform completely covered by short and stout setae, distinctly spaced and evenly distributed. Elytron smooth and shiny, with three longitudinal rows of punctures bearing long and slender setae. Metatibia with series of 12 evenly spaced spiniform setae at posteroventral margin. Metatarsomere I with similar row of four setae on posteroventral margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,220,1491]" box="[181,755,924,947]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis box="[181,290,924,947]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Ventral surface as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Guimarães &amp; Ferreira-Jr, 2017" authorityName="Guimarães &amp; Ferreira-Jr" authorityYear="2017" box="[519,664,924,947]" class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Canthysellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="527" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kukrutkato" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[519,664,924,947]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">C. kukrutkato</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[671,755,924,947]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,220,1491]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis box="[181,293,956,979]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Aedeagus.</emphasis>
Median lobe in lateral aspect elongate and thin, with ventral margin curved; dorsobasal margin sharply narrowing before midlength of median lobe and apex curved dorsally and rounded (
<figureCitation box="[357,465,1020,1043]" captionStart="Figs 5–8" captionStartId="4.[151,188,1505,1524]" captionTargetBox="[204,1072,228,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[195,1082,219,1480]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 5–8.Aedeagi of Canthysellus: a – median lobe, left lateral aspect, b – same, dorsal aspect, c – same, right lateral aspect, d – left lateral lobe (paramere), e – right lateral lobe. 5 – C. kukrutkato sp. nov.; 6 – C. putkarot sp. nov.; 7 – C. omawe sp. nov.; 8 – C. yawari sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315625" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315625/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Figs 6a, c</figureCitation>
); a long carina occurs on left side arising basally and ceasing apically, constituting the major part of left side (
<figureCitation box="[677,786,1052,1075]" captionStart="Figs 5–8" captionStartId="4.[151,188,1505,1524]" captionTargetBox="[204,1072,228,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[195,1082,219,1480]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 5–8.Aedeagi of Canthysellus: a – median lobe, left lateral aspect, b – same, dorsal aspect, c – same, right lateral aspect, d – left lateral lobe (paramere), e – right lateral lobe. 5 – C. kukrutkato sp. nov.; 6 – C. putkarot sp. nov.; 7 – C. omawe sp. nov.; 8 – C. yawari sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315625" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315625/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Figs 6a–c</figureCitation>
); in dorsal aspect, straight with apex slightly curved (
<figureCitation box="[381,460,1084,1107]" captionStart="Figs 5–8" captionStartId="4.[151,188,1505,1524]" captionTargetBox="[204,1072,228,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[195,1082,219,1480]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 5–8.Aedeagi of Canthysellus: a – median lobe, left lateral aspect, b – same, dorsal aspect, c – same, right lateral aspect, d – left lateral lobe (paramere), e – right lateral lobe. 5 – C. kukrutkato sp. nov.; 6 – C. putkarot sp. nov.; 7 – C. omawe sp. nov.; 8 – C. yawari sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315625" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315625/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Fig. 6b</figureCitation>
). Left lateral lobe, in lateral aspect, slender with a dense tuft of setae at apex; setae distinctly extending beyond dorsal margin (
<figureCitation box="[833,913,1116,1139]" captionStart="Figs 5–8" captionStartId="4.[151,188,1505,1524]" captionTargetBox="[204,1072,228,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[195,1082,219,1480]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 5–8.Aedeagi of Canthysellus: a – median lobe, left lateral aspect, b – same, dorsal aspect, c – same, right lateral aspect, d – left lateral lobe (paramere), e – right lateral lobe. 5 – C. kukrutkato sp. nov.; 6 – C. putkarot sp. nov.; 7 – C. omawe sp. nov.; 8 – C. yawari sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315625" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315625/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Fig. 6d</figureCitation>
). Right lateral lobe, in lateral aspect, broad and rounded ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[648,726,1148,1171]" captionStart="Figs 5–8" captionStartId="4.[151,188,1505,1524]" captionTargetBox="[204,1072,228,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[195,1082,219,1480]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 5–8.Aedeagi of Canthysellus: a – median lobe, left lateral aspect, b – same, dorsal aspect, c – same, right lateral aspect, d – left lateral lobe (paramere), e – right lateral lobe. 5 – C. kukrutkato sp. nov.; 6 – C. putkarot sp. nov.; 7 – C. omawe sp. nov.; 8 – C. yawari sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315625" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315625/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Fig. 6e</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,220,1491]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1180,1203]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Variation.</emphasis>
Due to the scarceness of specimens available, it is not possible to assess intraspecific variation.
</paragraph>
